Hardware History & Reproducibility Notes
One of the core design principles of the Hybrid Capacity–Expansion Framework (HFP) is computational accessibility.
The framework was originally developed and tested on a very low‑end HP laptop, and only later moved to the current Ryzen‑based system.

This matters because it demonstrates:

the equations are analytical, not brute‑force

the model does not require GPUs, clusters, or HPC resources

the results are reproducible on almost any machine

Original Development Hardware (2024–2025)
Device: HP consumer laptop

CPU: Dual‑core entry‑level mobile processor

RAM: 8 GB

GPU: Integrated graphics

Runtime:

Single‑galaxy rotation curve: 3–6 seconds

Joint MW+Draco fit: ~10 seconds

Full 14‑D stress test: under 1 minute

This was the hardware used to develop the first working ODIM/QSTF/Foundry engine and the original hybrid v3.0–v3.2 codebase.

Current Hardware (2026)
CPU: AMD Ryzen 5 8400F (6 cores @ 4.20 GHz)

RAM: 16 GB DDR5 @ 4800 MT/s

GPU: AMD Radeon RX 9060 XT (unused for HFP)

Storage: NVMe SSD

OS: Windows 11 Home

Current runtimes:

Single‑galaxy rotation curve: 0.5–1.0 seconds

Joint MW+DF4 fit: 3–5 seconds

Full 14‑D stress test: seconds to tens of seconds

Why This Matters
The fact that HFP ran on a low‑end HP laptop — and now runs even faster on a modest Ryzen gaming PC — shows:

the framework is fundamental, not computationally inflated

the math is clean, not dependent on numerical brute force

the results are accessible to anyone, anywhere

the model is scalable without requiring supercomputers

This is a major contrast to ΛCDM N‑body simulations, which require:

millions of CPU hours

GPU clusters

HPC centers

massive parallelization

HFP achieves comparable galactic‑scale predictions in seconds.
